        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Denholm</placeName>
                    <date>June 10<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>.</date>
                    <salute>Sir.</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I have just received your letter of yesterday’s date enclosing cheque for £25.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> and I now can only express my sincere thankfulness for your so amply &amp; readily affording me this which is much more than enough for my present requirements.</p>
<p>I will go in at once to Edinburgh and ascertain the 〈ex〉penses of the two routes to 〈In〉dia,<ref target="#foot.f3"/> I will also be careful in limiting my outfit to things really necessary.</p>
<p>You say in your letter that you would have me accept all that you are now giving me as a present. For such a kind act I really do not know how to thank you enough: I can only beg you to excuse me for this, and believe me most sincerely grateful; further that in my succeeding in India as I have now a strong hope from the infl〈uence〉 you have brought to bear upon me, it will be a pleasure for me to return the pecuniary assistance you are now so generously affording me.</p>
<p>I was much pleased to find that you had done me the honour of enclosing your Photograph.<ref target="#foot.f4"/> I have in vain tried to get through the Edinburgh pothographers and I did not like to take the liberty of asking it from you.</p>
<p>with best thanks for all these kindnesses. | I have the honour to remain | Sir | Your obed<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>. Servant | John Scott</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4524.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from John Scott, 8 June 1864</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The letter to Scott has not been found; however, CD’s Account book–cash account (Down House MS) records a gift of £25 to Scott on 10 June 1864. CD had offered to assist in paying the expenses of Scott’s journey to India (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4524.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from John Scott, 8 June 1864</ref> and n. 4).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Scott was considering whether to travel to India via the Cape of Good Hope or by an overland route (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4519.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. D. Hooker, [4 June 1864]</ref>, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4524.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from John Scott, 8 June 1864</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Scott refers to the photograph recently taken by CD’s eldest son, William Erasmus, and reproduced as the frontispiece to this volume. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4525.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. D. Hooker, 10 June [1864]</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
